04514nam a22007575i 9780520963559DE-B159720190920094934.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190920s2017    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209635597 a10.1525/97805209635592doi  a(DE-B1597)519078  a(OCoLC)966410507  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV8738b.S84 2018 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a365.66708209794612231 aSufrin, Carolyn, eauthor.10aJailcare :bFinding the Safety Net for Women behind Bars /cCarolyn Sufrin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I -- t1. Institutional Burden to Care -- t2. Triaging the Everyday, Every Day -- t3. Cultivating Ambiguity: Normalizing Care in the Jail Clinic -- t4. The Clinic Routine: Contradictions as Care -- tPart II -- t5. Gestating Care: Incarcerated Reproduction as Participatory Practice -- t6. Reproduction and Carceral Desire -- t7. Custody as Forced and Enforced Intimacy -- t8. At Home in Jail -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThousands of pregnant women pass through our nation's jails every year. What happens to them as they carry their pregnancies in a space of punishment? In this time when the public safety net is frayed, incarceration has become a central and racialized strategy for managing the poor. Using her ethnographic fieldwork and clinical work as an ob-gyn in a women's jail, Carolyn Sufrin explores how jail has, paradoxically, become a place where women can find care. Focusing on the experiences of incarcerated pregnant women as well as on the practices of the jail guards and health providers who care for them, Jailcare describes the contradictory ways that care and maternal identity emerge within a punitive space presumed to be devoid of care. Sufrin argues that jail is not simply a disciplinary institution that serves to punish. Rather, when understood in the context of the poverty, addiction, violence, and racial oppression that characterize these women's lives and their reproduction, jail can become a safety net for women on the margins of society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aPregnant womenxMedical carezCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aReproductive health serviceszCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aWomen prisonersxMedical carezCaliforniazSan Francisco. 4aanthropology. 4aethnography. 4afamilies of imprisoned moms. 4aimprisoned mother. 4ajudges. 4ajuries. 4alawyers. 4amaternal identity. 4amaternity ward. 4amoms and convicts. 4aobgyn. 4apregnancy and prison. 4apregnant incarcerated mothers. 4apregnant women. 4aprison guards. 4asociology. 4awomens jail. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963559423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780520963559.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles